when plug in a USB, the device driver in kernel generates a uevent which is then sent to user-space device manager daemon called udev, then udev creates a device node in /dev.

Dmesg is a tool to display messages from ring buffer in kernel.
$ dmesg                                      //prints messages generated by kernel

udevadm is a management tool for udev.
$ udevadm monitor                            //detects uevents

$ lspci
$ lsblk
$ lscpu
$ lsmem --summary
$ free -m                                    //total memory vs used memory
$ sudo lshw                                  //lshw shows hardware configuration


Linux Boot stages:
1. BIOD POST (Power-On-Self-Test): BIOS runs a POST test to ensure hardware components are funtioning correctly
2. Boot Loader (GRUB2): loads kernel into memory and hands over control
3. Kernel Initialization: initialize cpu, memory, interrupt handling etc. loads device drivers, mounts root file system, 
                          starts core kernel subsystems (networking, scheduler, security etc.), launches first user-space process (systemd)
4. INIT Process (systemd): to check the init system used, run $ ls -l /sbin/init
